t Peter A. Alces contends that such theories are misguided—so misguided that they undermine law and, ultimately, human thriving. Building on the foundation outlined in his previous work, The Moral Conflict of Law and Neuroscience, Alces further investigates the implications for legal doctrine and practice.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 02. Jun 2024) 0aLaw and ethics. 0aLawxPhilosophy. 0aNeurosciences. 7aPOLITICAL SCIENCE / General.2bisacsh  aneuroscience, morality, law, emotion, consequentialism, instrumentalism.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2023 Englishz978311131929208iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2023z9783111318912oZDB-23-DGG08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE Political Science 2023 Englishz978311131925408iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE Political Science 2023z9783111318677oZDB-23-PLW08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Chicago Complete eBook-Package 2023z978311079732940uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780226827490423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780226827490/original  a978-3-11-079732-9  University of Chicago Complete eBook-Package 2023b2023  a978-3-11-131925-4  EBOOK PACKAGE Political Science 2023 Englishb2023  a978-3-11-131929-2  EBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2023 Englishb2023  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aZDB-23-DGGb2023  aZDB-23-PLWb2023